<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06058001 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06058001 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  IRAQ; US; BANK; LOAN; AGRICULTURE; FARM; PRODUCT  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  American banks may see defaults on about $2 billion of loans with which Iraqbought a wide variety of U.S. farm products, an Agriculture Departmentofficial says.;    Most of the losses will be covered by American taxpayersunder terms of guarantees provided by USDA's Commodity Credit Corp. under theprogram. As of Jan. 7, about 1,000 claims had been filed by 10 banks forlosses totaling about $500 million.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  IRAQI DEFAULTS LOOMU.S. TAXPAYERS TO GET THE BILL  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Iraq halted payments;  The claims were the result of Iraq's failure to meetpayment schedules following its invasion of Kuwait last Aug. 2. One of theIraq's creditors is the National Bank of Kuwait, or specifically its New Yorkbranch.;    CCC Treasurer James R. Little said the defaulted Iraqi loansinvolved such products as wheat, rice, corn, soybeans, sugar, wool, eggs,cattle, poultry and tobacco,;    Banks that helped finance sales of U.S. farmcommodities to Iraq have filed thousands of claims seeking reimbursement.under the Agriculture Department's longstanding export credit guaranteeprogram.;    The purchases go back some years.;    'Buckets' of claims; Little said Tuesday that he had no fix on how many more claims have beenreceived since the Feb. 7 tabulation, but he acknowledged they have beencoming in &quot;by the bucketsful&quot; since then.;    The claims could total around$800 million in the fiscal year that began last Oct. 1. If Iraq does nothingfurther to resume payments, the CCC's total exposure has a face value loss ofslightly more than $2 billion, Little said.;    But he said CCC liabilitycovers only 98 percent of the loan principal and &quot;something less&quot; than thetotal interest that may be due.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Washington  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910227  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  February  </MONTH><PG.COL>  8E  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  269  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday February 27, 199100058001,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>